                <td bgColor="black"><textarea cols="70" name="Message" rows="12" wrap="VIRTUAL" onselect="storeCaret(this);" onclick="storeCaret(this);" onkeyup="storeCaret(this);" onchange="storeCaret(this);">[quote][i]Originally posted by tared[/i]
[br]Yawn... ok work is slow markets are shit so for my own entertainment.

A theoretical parse for one spell casting of horror from start to finish using the gear present in Tanatus magelo.

Horror
5.5 casting time
last 30 seconds
dmg base 2580

Tanatus Horror cast time including bard song.
3.85 seconds ( reductions of 15 % from spell haste 4 15% from the bard song ) 
--- or .70(5.5) = 3.85
--- assumption being made is that the two 15 percents are reduced from the original spell cast time.

Dmg of 3096 ( 0-25 % (vengeance of time) &lt;avg 12.5&gt; and 0-15% (bard song) &lt;avg 7.5&gt; ) 
--- or 1.2(2580) = 3096
--- assumption being made here is that the bard song is infact a 0-15 % increase and taht that increase is calculated from the inital dmg. &lt;havn't bothered to parse this since i get zero bard loving on raids&gt;

We also have the time before the dot takes effect on the mob that has been agreed to be between 0 and 6 seconds for an average of approximately 3 seconds. 

3096 dmg / (3.85 seconds of cast time + 3 seconds of "stall" time + 30 seconds of spell dmg time)

or

3096/36.85 = 84.016 dmg/sec max

Redone with different assumptions....

Now if the bard song is reduced after the intial reduction from focus items of vice versa (99 percent sure this isn't correct)

We have cast time of 3.97 seconds or &lt; .85(.85(5.5))&gt;
The same stall time of 3 seconds
Dmg now is 3120 or &lt;1.075(1.125(2580))&gt;
spell duration is 30 seconds again

or ... 3120/36.97 = 84.39 and change dmg/sec max

lets assume the dmg of the bard song is a fixed 15 percent &lt;like i said no idea havn't parsed&gt; or a dmg modifier of 27.5% ( 12.5% &lt;vengeance&gt; + 15% bard)

3.85 spell cast time
3 second stall time
dmg of 3289.5 or &lt;1.275(2580)&gt;
30 seconds spell time

3289.5/ 36.85= 89.267 and change dmg/sec max

anyone wearing out yet ?

so as you can see in the best circumstances your doing 89.267 dmg/sec in the worst 84 dmg/sec, using the gear you have as a basis. I would put my money on the 84 simply because i am betting that the bard song functions the same as all other focus items besides spell casting haste. Now why use the spell casting speed ? Because see you cannot do any dmg any other way with horror during that period of casting. You have to sit there and watch the speed of that bar go down. Now if we are talking about many spells all woven together perhaps this casting speed inportance changes a bit. But can you see now how much you are over estimating a spells dps ? With time burn (which is a total bitch to quantify in dot dps since the extension would effect tic count ) &lt; ext. of 0 to 20% = avg 10%, avg 10% into 30 seconds yields me 3 seconds of extra spell time, but the tic size is 6 so now i have a headache P &gt; and vengeance of time focuses and bard ... i might and i mean might get near 100 dps with horror.  However there are a hundred problems with all these assumptions the most basic being that a bard would bother playing his song for you, or that you would get into the bards groups for names. I think i have had that like once or twice tops. So to further recalc and make everyone puke and hate me more... 

Your horror dps minus a bard for one trial is....

.85(5.5) = 4.675 (spell haste 4 casting speed of horror)
3 seconds of "stall" time
30 seconds of real spell dmg time
dmg of 2902.5 or 1.125(2580) &lt; vengeance of time 0-25 -- average of 12.5%&gt;

2902.5/37.675 = 77.04 and change....

and in conclusion ...

The primary factor of all dps calculation is not the damage but the time involved. A single second of lag, wierd mob positioning, fd, casting speed, being caught in another casting time, or just generally not spaming the mob the second a spell wears off greatly decreases your dps. We have to greatly increase our dmg to over come errors in time. As you can see from this mathematic hell, large increases in dmg have far less effect on the dps calculation, then the seconds between casts.  Indeed using our fastest time from spell intialization to finish of 36.85 seconds(incidentally also the casting speed if using a ceramic skull of decay w/o bard song), it would take 3685 dmg from horror to produce 100 dps. At that rate you would need to be able to focus the spell at a 42.8% rate or have a 85 % focus item to intiate 100 dps. Now is that possible, sure it is. Add vengeance of eternity plus time burn and say a cord of potential (23 % spell haste) and you might get close or even surpass it. But again timeburn on this particular spell is not worth another 3 pages of calculations to determine the additive dmg hell. All i hope is that this shows folks the critical importance of time in the dps calculation. The item you chose for casting speed has incredible importance when determining your dps. While not as important as say the focus effects and extensions on paper, in practice hopefully you can see the difference. More then anything though parse it and really take a look at what is going on there. What is more interesting still is when u start adding the dps of mutiple different dots with different duration. But i digress it is time for me to get the hell out of here...

T


